        <h2 class="text-center text-lg text-uppercase my-0">Why solve a
          <strong>slider puzzle</strong>
        </h2>
        <hr class="divider">
        <img class="img-fluid float-left mr-4 d-none d-lg-block" src="../static/img/pupper.png" alt="">
        <p>If I gave you a 3x3 slider puzzle to solve, you could probably solve it from any amount of shuffling in under a minute. If you tried to explain how to solve it to someone it probably wouldn't take more than a couple more minutes. But if you tried to teach a computer to solve it, the problem changes entirely.</p>
        <p>We've probably seen stories of computers playing chess and beating the best players in the world, and we might have heard scary predictions about computers becoming self-aware. But, the idea of a machine learning to do something that we do is a fact of life that excites us and intrigues us, thus the slider puzzle.</p>
        <p>The slider puzzle is simple and straight-forward. There are predictable beginnings and endings. It only takes one play. It is scalable and has a very limited set of moves. It is a great candidate as a starting point for machine learning.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-faded p-4 my-4">
